[35mtutor >[0m A "mark on the metal" is what I mean by a test: some trace stamped into the coin itself — a crucible's leavings in the alloy, a graver's notch in the die — that would point wherever it points, whether the town liked the answer or not. Verrell had no such trace naming him; the town only had words.

So here's the one thing to nail down: why does having no mark count against a claim, rather than just counting as "nobody checked"? Put another way — what's missing that the crucible-mark and burin-mark both had, and Verrell's name never got?
